Executive Summary

The Autonomous Energy Production System (AEPS) is a new technological system with the aim of autonomously securing the energy supply (electricity and heat) of private households with extremely high economic efficiency of production and the possibility of storing energy.
The system serves as a platform technology for alternative types of generation of electricity and heat as well as various types of storage. Special emphasis is placed on efficient energy storage. Such a system has so far been viewed as desirable by energy experts and as sensible and efficient by economic experts, without concrete technological solutions even beginning to be discernible.
The AEPS aims to achieve the goals of security of supply for households, economical production of energy with high environmental compatibility. All forms of private energy generation (e.g. solar, wind, heat pumps, etc.) can also be integrated into the AEPS.
The system has been developed by experts in automation and energy technology since 2015. The prototype has been fully functional for 2 years. The system has also been providing data for a year that shows that the objectives of self-sufficiency, efficiency and clear environmental friendliness have been fully achieved.
Even high current peaks, for example due to fast charging of e-cars, can be represented without any problems, because the current storage media used are based on modern capacitor technology. This means that charging and discharging processes only take a little time, so little that depending on the batteries used, a full charge of a 90 KW battery takes little time. The charging process is handled by the battery, which is slowly charged with less than 3 KW. The public power grid is therefore not required for the charging process and the stability of the public grid is not affected.
The system does not require any special approval in Germany, since the required additional components have already been integrated into the control cabinet technology of the French Schneider Group.
The first systems are currently being delivered to buyers. A further 150 units will be delivered within a year. Due to the low number of items in the initial phase, no marketing measures were taken. Nevertheless, many orders for the system have already been received. In the small series production phase, the product is to be further prepared for mass production. After a lead time of two years, the construction of a Gigafactory in Europe is planned.
The initiators assume that the TESLA location in Berlin/Grünheide has very good prerequisites for a settlement. Should the planned battery factory not be completed there, existing buildings and staff could be used. The German Operational Unit S.A.H. and some suppliers are settled.

In parallel to the German project, a separate company is to be founded in Asia. This is to be financed independently and to develop the Asian market by bringing in the know-how of the European companies. One possibility for a settlement would be Weifang, in close proximity to the supplier of the generator. Here, too, a small series production is to be set up. The product itself will be based on the basic technical considerations of the German system, but reflect the specific requirements of the Asian market. In terms of company law, the Chinese company would belong to the Swiss holding company TCS AG. Be established as a subsidiary. The German company would then serve the European market and the Chinese company the Asian market. Technological knowledge could then be exchanged between societies. In order to set up production on the Asian market, it is intended to take on a partner for the Chinese company. This partner should invest in the Chinese company with equity. Likewise, the manufacturing process and sales should be taken over by the Chinese partner. The know-how is initially made available to the Chinese company by the European parent company and can be used for the complete market development. Both companies should later interact moderately with know-how, so that they could possibly undertake joint sourcing. In the first phase, a capital requirement of EUR 150 million would be necessary.
In phase 2, a Gigafactory would then be required for mass production. The funds then required would then have to be specified. To do this, additional equity would have to be raised to strengthen the company. It is also conceivable that capital can already be raised via the stock exchange at this point in time, especially since the expected sales and profits will allow such an undertaking.
General conditions for the electricity market in Europe and Germany 

Europe is in the Green Deal fever. The European Commission's Green Deal of December 2019, which envisages spending one trillion euros over the next ten years, aims for a sustainable EU economy. This goal is to be achieved by seeing climate and environmental policy challenges as opportunities in all policy areas and by making the transition fair and inclusive for everyone; he specifically aims for climate neutrality in 2050, the first step of which is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by at least 55%.
10 years earlier, a discussion about energy and climate policy starting points had started in Germany. Associated with this was the demand for a substantial reduction in primary energy requirements. Nuclear power and fossil fuels such as hard coal, lignite and mineral oil should disappear from the energy mix. Natural gas was only tolerated as a transitional technology. Compensations for fossil energy production should be replaced by green energies (wind and solar). This was inevitably linked to the shift in power generation from central production to a decentralized structure. In the meantime, 9 nuclear power plants have been taken off the grid in Germany, and the last three power plants will be taken off the grid next month.

Germany has accepted the following risks with the energy transition:

Technological risks due to the necessary system integration of renewable energies are included in generation and distribution. There is a risk here of moving from a demand-oriented electricity concept to a supply-oriented concept. This would jeopardize security of supply in the classic form.
Compatibility challenges in the form of the creation of interfaces between conventional and new technologies, controllable power plants and balancing energy for the entire grid are particularly in demand
Grid infrastructure challenges, transmission grids and distribution grids
funding challenges; From today's perspective, up to EUR 900 billion must be invested in the power grids
Challenges for electricity consumers: Price trends for electricity Security of supply
The storage media for electricity (e.g. hydrogen, methane or just electricity storage) are not yet available in sufficient quantities.
This scenario for the private consumer is supplemented by the heat transition, which, in addition to improving the thermal insulation of buildings in order to reduce consumption, is also aimed directly at private households and aims to get rid of heating systems powered by fossil fuels. Instead, these heaters are to be substituted by electricity-driven heat pumps.
At the same time, a mobility turnaround is to be implemented in Europe. Electromobility is seen as the key to climate-friendly mobility. Since the operation of electric vehicles, especially in connection with regeneratively generated electricity, produces significantly less CO2 (carbon dioxide) emissions.
There are currently around 80 electric vehicle models from German manufacturers on the market (as of July 2022). In order to make the use of electric vehicles more attractive, the federal government has decided to provide additional impetus in the form of temporary purchase incentives, further funds for the expansion of the charging infrastructure, additional efforts in the public procurement of electric vehicles and tax measures.
All of this makes it clear that the transition from conventional energy sources to renewable energy sources already challenges the entire system. The measures aimed at directing the private consumption of fossil energy from the heating system to the heat pump and from the combustion engine to the electric motor are leading to considerable supply uncertainties for the entire system.

General conditions for the electricity market in Europe and Germany 

In the past, the generation of electricity in Germany had to comply with three objectives (§1 EnWG). These were:
• security of supply
• Cost efficiency and
• Environmental sustainability

These goals have long been considered equal. With the energy turnaround, the goal of environmentally friendly production of electricity has become the focus of the power supply. Although an improved ecological balance has been achieved with the energy transition, the two other goals of cost efficiency and security of supply have inevitably been negatively affected. The goal of reducing the amount of electricity in Germany, originally envisaged in 2010, has at best only been achieved to a very limited extent, taking into account the pandemic effects of 2019 and 2020.

Fig. Electricity consumption in Germany: Source Federal Environment Agency
At the same time, however, the costs for electricity in Germany have risen significantly in recent years and have almost doubled since 2012. They are an expression of a decentralized form of power generation from renewable energy sources such as wind and sun. The BDEW/Ernest Young study came to the following conclusion: “In 2021, Germany’s households had the highest electricity prices in a European comparison due to surcharges and taxes. The graphic below shows the costs for a household with a consumption of 3500 KWh/year.
Source: Bundesverband der Energie- und Wasserwirtschaft, 2023
The question arises as to whether the increased electricity costs are a slip-up, possibly caused by the Ukraine war, and whether falling electricity costs can be expected in the future? The estimates of the state Federal Network Agency say the following: "According to the scenario framework for the "Network Development Plan Electricity" on which the analysis is based and approved by the Federal Network Agency, around 14 million electricity-powered heat pumps will heat buildings in 2037 and 32 million electric cars in Germany to be on the road. This means that there will be a significantly increasing proportion of electricity in the energy supply. At the same time, the cost of electricity is likely to continue to rise.
According to estimates by Oliver Wyman, the electricity demand in Germany will increase by 70% by 2037 as a result of the elimination of fossil fuels and their/partial substitution by electricity. The electricity mix should also change by 2037 and be made up as follows:

Source: Oliver Wyman
It becomes clear that the supply situation cannot generally be remedied via price mechanisms, since the physical capacity of the network can only be expanded with new power lines. At most, a shift in electricity consumption is possible with the aim of capping peak demand. Networks are therefore limitational factors for power consumption.

An important point in the past in Germany was that the amount of electricity remained constant over a long period of time, despite the strong effect of further electrification. This has been achieved through corresponding savings in consumption and the increase in efficiency. The increased volume can be accounted for by an increased number of electrical devices.
Power grids under pressure 

The power supply in Germany is ensured by an energy infrastructure, an interaction of power plants, transformers, storage facilities and lines. A stable energy supply is indispensable as the basis for growth and prosperity. The power grid is divided into different voltage levels. 


The backbone of the energy infrastructure in Germany is formed by the electricity transport networks of the transmission system operators. Different network operators are responsible for different areas – from extra high voltage to low voltage. At the highest voltage level, the republic's "electricity highways" transport large amounts of electricity with up to 380 kilovolts directly from the power plants over long distances to the distribution grids in the regions. In addition, the transmission grids connect the German power grid with that of the neighboring countries and thus enable the cross-border exchange of energy in Europe. The transmission network has a total length of more than 35,000 km.

In the regions themselves, the electricity is gradually being regulated down to a lower voltage so that households can finally get electricity from the socket with only 230 or 400 volts. So-called distribution network operators connect local power consumers such as individual households to the power grid at this low-voltage and medium-voltage level. At the regional level, the electricity is also distributed by distribution network operators via medium-voltage networks. Buyers here include larger consumers, such as energy-intensive companies.
However, the type of generation has an impact not only on the costs but also on the grids and thus on the physical provision of electricity. Renewable energies are primarily generated in northern Germany, but most of the electricity is consumed in southern Germany. With this shift in production to the north and heavy consumption in southern Germany, the existing transmission grids (380kv) must be strengthened. However, the required network expansion is progressing slowly. In 2021, instead of the planned EUR 32.6 billion (of which EUR 21.4 billion for generation and EUR 9 billion for grid expansion), investments of just EUR 6.1 billion were made, of which only EUR 1.5 billion went into grid expansion. 
Nevertheless, the data published by the Federal Network Agency on the supply disruptions to be reported by the energy companies looks quite good. 


According to this, only 12.7 minutes of supply interruptions were recorded on average in Germany in 2021. Regarding the "supply interruptions", however, the shutdown is not voluntary or forced by the network operators.
System services are intended to ensure the power supply 

With the simultaneous conversion of energy production in Germany to renewable energies, the e-mobility and heating transition, network operation is faced with considerable challenges. In order to ensure high quality, reliability and safety in power transmission and distribution, the frequency, voltage and load of the equipment must be kept within permissible limits. In addition, disturbances must be returned to the normal range. These tasks required to maintain the power supply are referred to as system performance. A distinction is made between operational management, frequency stability, voltage stability and supply restoration. 
As early as 2014, a study  commissioned by the Ministry of Economic Affairs pointed out that with the increasing integration of renewable energy systems into the distribution grids, the expansion of renewable energy systems will require a significant expansion of the German distribution grids and that grid fees will increase and differ even more strongly from region to region. The Federal Network Agency also addresses this point in a study from 2017. There it says in points 7 to 9: 
"7. Active congestion management is becoming more important in a power supply system in which far more than half of the generation volumes come from renewable energies. As part of congestion management, the network operator can make contractual agreements with the market side for network-related purposes on the provision of network-related flexibility with market players and negotiate the remuneration.
8. The curtailment of renewable energy plants is a flexibility option. It should be available to network operators in the event of network congestion if it is the most cost-effective option still available.
9. Flexibility that is beneficial to the grid should be classified as a whole and including the curtailment of renewable energy systems in the “yellow phase” of the “traffic light”. All expenses for grid-friendly flexibilities should be included in the efficiency comparison within the framework of the ARegV in order to create equivalent incentives.”
dena commissioned a study back in 2016, not least to clarify the question of what conditions need to be created for a stable power grid. The conventional power plants provide the majority of the system services that are required to stabilize the power grid and thus ensure system security. With the increasing shares of fluctuating feed-in from renewable energies, the market shares of conventional power plants are decreasing. In hours with high generation from wind and photovoltaics, conventional power plant output is still connected to the grid to a small extent. The transmission system operators (TSO) are responsible for compensating for imbalances that arise in the overall balance due to unforeseeable short-term deviations from generation and load forecasts. The system service "frequency maintenance" is provided for this purpose
In the first moment of frequency deviations, the instantaneous reserve makes an important contribution to frequency stability, it immediately dampens frequency changes. However, the instantaneous reserve is currently provided by conventional power plants (nuclear power plants and coal-fired power plants) as the inertia of rotating masses. In recent years, the number of grid interventions in Germany has increased exponentially. 


Number of intrusions into the network, Source: Bundesnetzagentur 
Number of interventions The management measures for stabilizing the network are shown below.

Generation management: targeted curtailment of feed-in from renewable energy systems permitted for a few hours of the year,
Reactive power management: Expansion of the provision of reactive power through decentralized generation systems.
Load management: Targeted influencing of loads for a few hours of the year
Intelligent network technologies Intelligent network technologies, i.e. controllable local network transformers, voltage regulators and high-temperature conductor cables

At present, however, the share of renewable energies in power generation in Germany is growing significantly faster than the expansion of the grid, which is required to transport the energy. As a consequence, temporary transmission bottlenecks can arise. In the transmission grid, a "grid bottleneck" occurs when the electricity produced by a generator cannot reach the consumer due to a lack of transmission capacity. Such a situation can have various causes. To avoid these bottlenecks or, if necessary, eliminate them, various measures are available to the transmission system operators during ongoing network operation. These are:
• Feed-in management and that
• Redispatch Management.

Both methods serve to bridge temporary bottlenecks.
Due to the above-mentioned fluctuations in the electricity to be fed into the grid, the grid capacities are not sufficient to transport the total electricity generated. In such cases, the grid operators use the feed-in management (EisMan) to avoid grid bottlenecks and to ensure security of supply. In these situations, the grid operators feed less energy into the grid from the electricity generated from renewable energies, which is generally given priority.
This procedure differs from peak shaving (redispatch), which is already used in network planning. Redispatch is a measure to control the flow of electricity. Certain parts of the power grid are relieved using the laws of physics. With redispatch, the power plant output is specifically reduced on one side of the line and increased on the other side. This reduces the total current on the line. The necessary agreements are made between the respective network operator and the responsible power plant operator.
These intervention options are to be expanded in Germany on January 1, 2024. A corresponding ordinance from the Federal Network Agency is in the works.

The dangers of unpredictable power generation from renewable energies, the heating and transport transition have left their mark on those responsible for politics, as the following analysis of the last two points will show.
Mobility and heat transition - drivers for higher electricity demand 

Electromobility is seen worldwide as the key to climate-friendly mobility. Since the operation of electric vehicles, especially in connection with regeneratively generated electricity, produces significantly less CO2 (carbon dioxide) emissions. In addition, according to the proponents, electric vehicles will be able to compensate for fluctuations in wind and solar power in the future as mobile electricity storage devices. The Federal Republic of Germany plans to have around 32 million electric cars in use by 2032.

Source: K&B

From 2024, at least 500,000 heat pumps should be installed in Germany every year and 32 million electric cars should be on German roads.  By 2030, half of the energy consumed is to be generated in a climate-neutral manner. "Against this background, electric heat pumps as a highly efficient heating technology represent a promising option."  By 2037, around 14 million electricity-powered heat pumps will heat buildings.
The Federal Network Agency has warned of an overload of the electricity grid in Germany due to the increasing number of private electric charging stations and electricity-driven heat pumps. "If a large number of new heat pumps and data stations continue to be installed, then overload problems and local power failures in the distribution network are to be feared if we do not act." The network agency has therefore published a key issues paper that provides for temporary electricity rationing for heat pumps and electric car charging stations in times of high network utilization. Network operators are to throttle the power supply of the systems compulsorily and in a centrally coordinated manner. The operationalization plans are scheduled to come into effect on January 1, 2024. However, heaters and chargers should not be completely disconnected from the power supply during critical phases. "We want to guarantee a minimum supply at all times". Even with electricity rationing, private charging stations would be able to obtain enough electricity to charge the battery of an e-car within 3 hours for a range of 50 kilometers. In addition, "almost trouble-free continued operation should be possible. for a large number of heat pumps" (President of the Federal Network Agency).
dena also supports these demands of the Federal Network Agency in a current statement by the German Energy Agency on the key issues paper of the Federal Network Agency: "The electrification of the heating and transport sector is a central component on the way to climate neutrality” . According to the Federal Government, the number of electric cars should therefore increase from just under 1 million to 15 million by 2030 and the number of heat pumps from around 1 million to 6 million. This rapid increase in new consumers poses major challenges for the power grids. This is because the low-voltage networks are usually not designed for peak loads, which can occur if these new consumers draw electricity at the same time. The necessary reinforcement and expansion of the distribution grids will not be able to keep pace with the rapid development of electromobility and heat pumps. However, so that the use of electric cars and heat pumps is not held up by capacity bottlenecks in the electricity distribution network, these new consumers should be controlled in such a way that the simultaneity is reduced and bottlenecks are avoided. This flexibilization of electricity demand is a measure that can be implemented in the short term to quickly integrate new consumption devices and avoid network overloads.” This essentially involves changing paragraph 14a of the EnWG.
This paragraph regulates the handling of new controllable consumer devices in private households in the low-voltage network, i.e., private charging points for electric cars, heat pumps and refrigeration systems as well as battery storage if they draw electricity. In its old version, it already enabled the distribution network operator to control these consumption devices to avoid overloads. However, this required a separate and voluntary conclusion of contract with the respective consumer. The following stipulations apply to “controllable consumption devices”:
1. Controllable consumer devices must be firmly connected.
2. The electricity requirement is recorded using a separate measuring device (additional meter space).
3. Control takes place via an intelligent measuring system in connection with a control box,

However, only a few heat pumps currently have a gateway to the supplier. They can therefore also not be switched off immediately. However, there are already measures that allow the energy supplier to intervene within the framework of the existing contracts, as can be shown using the example of a specific supplier. 

For example, NETZGESELLSCHAFT NIEDERRHEIN MBH, Krefeld, regulates in its electricity contracts with private customers that the electricity supply to the heat pumps in its network area is interrupted for up to six hours a day, but not for more than two consecutive hours.: "Until the installation of intelligent measuring devices with a controllable gateway, the release times of heat pumps in the grid area of ​​NETZGESELLSCHAFT NIE-DERRHEIN MBH (NGN) are controlled by timers via load-optimizing switching times. The selection, installation and parameterization of this device is always carried out by the network operator." 
NGN electricity customers currently have two options for electric cars: “All charging devices for electric vehicles always have the right to choose to install a timer. In the commissioning order for electricity, select the charging station/wall box requirement type according to §14a for the installation of a timer. If you do not want the e-charging device to be interrupted, select Household here, the supply to the charging device will not be interrupted and you will not receive a separate measurement."
This means that interventions in the power supply for private households are already possible before the Federal Network Agency issues a corresponding ordinance. The case of regulation of grid overload is therefore already a reality in electricity contracts.




Electromobility and charging infrastructure

In a recent study, Deloitte asked consumers in various countries about their purchasing behavior in relation to electromobility and came across similar trends, but with quite different focuses. Among other things, they were asked about their preference for electric vehicles, behavior when charging the electric vehicle and fears about possible bottlenecks in the power grid system, which are presented below.
 
Source: Deloitte: 2023 Global Automotive Consumer Study Key findings: Global focus countries 


Source: Deloitte 2023

The number of electric vehicles in Germany reached around EUR 1 million at the end of 2022. In China, on the other hand, there are already around 10 million vehicles on the road. In addition, around 30% of the registered vehicles were electrically powered last year.


Deloitte: 2023 Global Automotive Consumer Study Key findings: Global focus countries, Jan. 2023

Due to the increasing number of new registrations of battery electric vehicles and plug-in hybrids, the new target of 15 million electric vehicles by 2030 and the further development of the EU fleet limits, the charging infrastructure requirement in Germany will continue to increase significantly in the coming years.


Source: EY

The successful grid integration of electromobility into the power grid is a central prerequisite for this. Against this background, the National Platform (NPM) - Future of Mobility (NPM) discussed the topic of grid integration of private charging infrastructure again. The aim of the report is to show cross-industry points of consensus and to develop recommendations for action. The focus was on the possibilities for preventive grid-friendly control of private charging infrastructure.
The industries involved agree that with preventive grid-supportive control there is mutual responsibility depending on the traffic light phase (green/amber/red) and that a legal basis must urgently be created that provides both reliability and plannability compared to today's status quo and offers the necessary scope for technological innovations. Technical, legal, financial and procedural questions must be clarified in order to implement preventive grid-supportive control in the sense of a common, cross-industry basic understanding. In addition to the results of preventive grid-supportive control, the NPM also recommends the following points:


Timely completion of the technical work on the Smart Meter Gateway (SMGW) and control box with a focus on controllability functionality
Enabling alternative solutions to the SMGW for the start-up period, which can meet the requirements for preventive grid-supportive control without SMGW
The strengthening of three-phase AC charging with 11 kW
The simplification and acceleration of grid expansion

Based on the requirements, the necessity of restricting access to the German power grid becomes clear.
But the strong growth of electric vehicles will also continue in China.

The holistic Green Safe House energy system

The Green Safe House was developed by experienced engineers from industrial plant construction.
SAH GmbH has been active in the industrial engineering of large-scale petrochemical plant construction for 20 years. She is not only the initiator and driving force in the development of the self-sufficiency EMS system, but also developed the system for her own company and put it into operation. An in-depth global market analysis has led to the conclusion that there are not even remotely functional systems on the market that meet SAH's commercial requirements for a total cost of ownership with an adequate return on investment on the one hand and the technical requirements on the other. After the sobering result of the extensive technical and economic market analysis, SAH felt compelled to independently develop a fully functional, economically viable self-sufficient EMS system. Using all existing cross-departmental knowledge from the engineering of all affiliated companies consisting of
- Industrial petrochemical engineering sector
- the military engineering field
- the nuclear power plant area, energy distribution planning and construction
- the process engineering area
a fully functional system should be realized - via a complete re-engineering, based on the latest state of the art in the regenerative energy sector.
The Green House energy system aims to comply with the energy policy triad
• security of supply
• Cost efficiency
• environmental compatibility.

This goes so far that the GreenSafe House system can be operated entirely with green energy. The energy required for the generator can already be obtained from hydrogen (hydrogen readyness).
From the point of view of the developers, the security of supply of the power supply is no longer guaranteed due to the expansion of the grids, the strong increase in renewable forms of energy with their strong fluctuations and the mobility and heating transition. It remains to be seen whether sufficient imported electricity will be available and whether the planned shutdowns and load shifts will not have serious negative consequences for private consumers.
The sharply rising electricity and energy costs are unlikely to decrease in the next few years either. In Germany, the energy costs for an average household were EUR 0.48 and the trend is rising. The cost structures have deteriorated significantly due to the need for network expansions and the development of additional renewable electricity capacities in Germany.

The Safe Green House System and its components	
General System Requirements

The self-sufficient EMS system was created from the experience of plant construction. The ideas relating to efficiency and safety were derived from this area and transferred to residential and commercial buildings. The core objective of the engineering process was to develop a robust system from standard components and new storage components in order to meet the goals of self-sufficiency and efficiency.
The following requirements were placed on the system during development:
Functionality regarding the three overarching objectives
Longevity of the system and its components in terms of a total cost of ownership consideration
Use of standard components from mass production for reasons of cost and maintenance
Strict selection process of different suppliers
Adaptation of the modular components through individual engineering
All essential components are TCS branded and thus individualized
Engineering of the Green Safe House product in terms of mass production capability
Engineering to minimize installation costs
Easy handling of the whole system for the user
Easy installation for craftsmen
Minimization of maintenance costs
Acceptance of warranty services also for the batteries
The components of the Green Safe House System result from the technical function of the system. The following system requirements therefore apply:
1. Self-sufficiency of the system
2. Integration of all forms of energy production in the system
3. Speed ​​of provision of electricity and fulfillment of high demands on performance
4. System security, esp. in terms of memory components

Self-sufficiency can only be achieved if the power purchase can be realised independently of the public grid over a period of several weeks.
In the full version of the system, all forms of generation from solar, wind and heat pump generators can be included. The system establishes the connection to the public grid based on a 380 V three-phase system. This makes it possible to exchange the Safe Green House concept with the public power grid. The batteries can thus be fed by their own power generation or fed from the grid. If desired and sensible, the system can also supply stored electricity to the grid.
If the public grid does not supply electricity, the current power consumption can be maintained. Either the renewable energies supply the electricity directly or the required amounts of electricity are made available by the storage facility. Load restrictions or shifts of the current demand are not necessary. The changeover from grid power to microgrid power takes place automatically within a millisecond interval.
Another important aspect of the system relates to security. As shown, there are not inconsiderable risks with traditional lithium batteries, which do not exist with capacitor technology.

Main components  - Storage medium and Control cabinet

The main components are the control cabinet as the heart of the system, through which all elements of the micro network are integrated, and the control cabinet
Conventional lithium batteries are used in electric cars as well as in many other applications. Price advantages and marketability are often mentioned. However, two aspects are negative. On the one hand, lithium batteries are classified as dangerous goods in international transport law. They are therefore relevant to the diverse regulations for the transport of dangerous goods. Secondly, each charging process reduces the service life.
Lithium batteries can cause fires if they are handled improperly or if defects suddenly occur. Particularly high temperatures are reached, which can lead to major damage in the area. Batteries and accumulators containing lithium (ion) are currently widespread in various types and with various chemical compositions. The high performance levels of the lithium batteries are achieved through module combinations of individual cells, each with a nominal voltage of around 3.6 V. The function of the modules should be secured by battery management systems and other protective mechanisms. Nevertheless, fire, electrical short circuits and the leakage of caustic liquids are a not inconsiderable risk, so that the batteries are seen as dangerous goods in terms of class 9 ADR/RID (various dangerous substances and objects).
dena II comments on the suitability of lithium batteries for balancing mains voltages about the use of batteries as storage in the event of mains fluctuations: "Chemical batteries have extremely fast response times. They can call up their full power within a few milliseconds. There are storage losses that can amount to 5% of the stored energy per month. The efficiencies of chemical batteries are very high, sometimes exceeding 95%. However, the service life of a battery is reduced with each charging cycle, so that the technical service life is exhausted after 3 - 12 years of regular use. The investment in a battery storage system must have paid for itself within this time window.”  And he concludes: “Battery storage systems are comparatively unsuitable for peak shaving because, despite the high level of efficiency, there is heavy wear and tear on the system if it is frequently charged and discharged.” 
The redox flow battery is seen differently: “Redox flow batteries use technology that is available today, all components are technically mature. In contrast to conventional chemical batteries, they consist of a converter and a separate storage unit. which makes the configuration more flexible. Due to the very short start-up times, redox flow batteries are suitable for providing balancing energy. The high level of efficiency would allow peak shaving, but the upper limit of charging cycles is an obstacle, as each charging process has a negative impact on service life. 
dena comes to a different conclusion when it comes to supercapacitors. “In smaller applications, supercapacitors are technically available today. However, large applications with an energy density of over 20 kWh per m² are still in the development phase. While conventional batteries can no longer be used after a few 1000 charging cycles, well over 100,000 charging cycles can be achieved in supercaps. Due to the low energy density, supercapacitors play a role in mobile applications. With an efficiency of between 80% and 95%, they have low operating and maintenance costs.“ dena comes to the conclusion that under the conditions at that time, the use of supercapacitors as a medium for compensating for voltage fluctuations was out of the question.
Since 2021, however, supercapacitors with the required technical properties have been available. New production techniques have made it possible to significantly reduce the cost of supercapacitors and use them for the intended application. With the condenser technology, which in China, but also in Germany at the Technical University of Munich was developed, the capacitor technologist can not only compete with the lithium battery technology, but also outperform in individual performance criteria. Lithium batteries no longer have any advantages in terms of weight and capacity. About the charging cycles and the charging and discharging speed, the capacitors are superior to the lithium batteries. The capacitor storage is also competitive in price and the previous significant weight disadvantages of the capacitors compared to batteries have now been eliminated.
The heart of the Green Safe House is the control cabinet technology platform. It controls all energy producers, for example according to a merit order system. Here it is decided when and how the batteries are charged, then what amounts of electricity are used, whether and if so how much hot water is generated in the boilers. It is also decided how long the heat pump will supply energy on cold days and when it makes sense to switch on the generator and cover the electricity requirement and at the same time fully charge the batteries or produce hot water. The platform takes a variety of different measurements, makes them available to the user. The management parameters used can be varied depending on external effects. If the price of electricity falls sharply and the corresponding quantities are available, electricity could also be drawn from the public grid again. The large number of control options should only be outlined and would go far beyond the scope of such a presentation. It should also be mentioned that the entire technology in the platform control cabinet consists of devices that were specially developed by TCS.
The remaining overall system components are made up of further developed, proven standard components.
• TCS BAFA approved heat pumps
• Three-phase mains replacement generator based on solar technology
• Needs-based backup power system (similar to CHP), which was jointly developed by leading outfitters for the energy system of luxury yachts with TCS for the Green Safe House Project
• Functionally new inverters, also equipped with the appropriate TCS technology to meet the requirements of the Green Safe House Microgrid
• ABN offers indoor small distributor technology, meter space, distributor and converter technology for efficient use in both residential and functional buildings as well as for commercial buildings. All systems correspond to the current standards and technical application guidelines.

The platform system has an efficient summer operation, in which the PV electricity/wind and the heat pump as well as the storage can be used optimally. In the cold season, the backup power system with an overall system efficiency of 187% is optimally activated to cover peak loads. Since this generator only works sequentially in the overall system with an output of only 7.5 KW, the overall consumption load is very low.
The coordinated overall integration of the TCS developed components (rectifier, solar system, heat pump and storage medium) and their optimal use in the overall system enable system self-sufficiency and low consumption and the very small ecological footprint in the overall period. The fuel oil used here can easily be replaced by alternative green energy carriers, low-Co2 fuels (bioethanol, hydrogen). As a result, this system is the only one to date that already fully meets all the targeted ecological and economic goals.

Green Safe-Charging House as partial variant

A variant of the Green Safe House concept is to be outlined here. It is based on the same principles and integrates a wall box, which is also included in the Green Safe House variant.
A self-sufficient system offers a number of special features, especially with regard to electromobility. The capacitors used can store large amounts of energy very quickly and release them just as quickly. With the Green House System, the entire battery can be charged in a short time, if necessary exclusively with solar power, if the appropriate storage capacities are installed. If, in addition to the standard 15 KW, you install about two more packs of 15 KW each, an electric vehicle with 100 KW can be fully charged in just over two hours.

If you want to charge your battery quickly and independently of the power grid, you can therefore install additional capacitor storage. The corresponding connections are available. This decision is a trade-off between utility and convenience.
However, this makes the user independent of the availability of electricity from the grid. In times of insecure power grids, this is a decision that a buyer can make according to their needs.

In addition, such a user makes himself independent of the availability of corresponding amounts of electricity from the grid or public charging stations. In summer, the batteries of the e-car can be charged safely, quickly and mostly with full availability using your own solar system. Private users can thus fill up their own green electricity during the sunny months.

Leaving aside the question of personal preferences when choosing the storage capacity of the self-sufficient EMS, it can be said that the standard variant with 15 KW storage capacity without the use of bioethanol, a system previously unavailable (household energy and e-mobility) achieved green footprint is generated.

Temporal steps of the self-sufficient EMS prototype system 

The following overview shows the development maturity of the system

The overview above shows that all development work on the system has been completed, that it has been running as a prototype for two years. There are currently several dozen complete systems that have been ordered. The construction of self-sufficient charging stations was also required. In view of the preparatory work that is still necessary for mass production to be ready for series production, these approaches are being pursued with great caution. The potential in the Stuttgart and Düsseldorf area alone would be sufficient to realize the planned annual sales.
The first five systems will be delivered by May. Then the logistical planning also proved to be sustainable and, in a second step, a second round of orders has been carefully worked on for several months.
For the German market it is also of interest that the BAFA has meanwhile sent out notices for a probation of subsidies. This means that systems in Germany will be subsidized by the state with the expected subsidy rate of almost 50%.

Sourcing and Distribution 

The Green House System branding is an essential part of the system. Not only does it protect the brand, but it shows that the components are mass-produced, but have been further developed for the purposes of this system for adaptation. This makes it clear that the aim here is to be able to offer a completely new system.
In times of supply chain troubles, sourcing is key. In the present case, TCS components are manufactured by suppliers from Asia and Germany. In most cases, we have been in contact with the Asian and German suppliers for years. The following components, for which there are firm delivery capability commitments, are of major importance for the main components:

The core elements of the technology control cabinets platform are also imported from Germany due to the technological lead. It is planned to have the platform technology control switchgear built in China in the short term. Corresponding talks are currently being held.
After Phase I, the measures for efficient manufacture of the Safe Green House product are taken. Moreover, the product has been technologically simplified in such a way that electricians can easily assemble it as a compact system. Refinements, especially to further improve efficiencies and supply chains, are still to be made (Ikea Steck-Regal ready for series production). Due to the scarcity of components, only limited quantities can be produced in the first two years. From today's perspective, the sales target of 1500 systems p.a. is possible. After the first two years, large-scale production will be launched, for which further investments may then be necessary. However, an IPO can then also be considered to finance the capital requirement. 
The range of systems is aimed at private individuals/commercialists who strive for self-sufficiency and want to produce efficient energy. In particular, the offer is aimed at people who want to replace or renew heating systems.
The current situation with the limited production quantities (compared to the market possibilities) of 1500 pieces in the first two years make comprehensive sales efforts of all kinds seem inadequate. For the first two years it is sufficient to sell through a network of energy consultants. We assume that in the first phase sales of 1500 pieces per year will be completely unproblematic. As the Deloitte study has shown, people in Asia (China, Korea, Japan) are primarily interested in charging e-cars at home. The enormous growth rates of electromobility in China and other Asian countries will ensure that there will continue to be a high demand for private charging stations in the future. In addition, the public charging stations in China are very concentrated in urban areas, so that buyers who do not live in urban areas are likely to be very interested in an independent way of charging independently and at home.
We assume that despite the comparatively high price, demand will clearly exceed supply. Because alternative technologies rely on the use of lithium batteries. Battery technology is viewed much more critically in China than in America or Europe, as the current study by Deloitte also shows. In particular, it is the risk of fire hazards that is likely to play a role in deciding against a lithium battery.

Sehr geehrter Herr Heyd!
Gerne bestätige ich Ihnen nach unserem soeben geführten Telefonat, dass Sie Ihr
Unternehmen, TCS GmbH durch unser anerkanntes Institut einer Zertifizierung nach dem Militärstandard der NATO Staaten AQAP (Allied Quality Assurance Publications) in der Version 2000:2007 unterziehen. Den Auftrag hierfür erhielten wir im Dezember 2011. Die voraussichtliche Zertifizierung wird im Oktober 2012 fertig gestellt sein.
Die notwendigen Arbeitsschritte der verschiedenen Audits ergaben bisher ausschließlich die Erfüllung verschiedener geforderter Voraussetzungen, die zum Erhalt der Zertifizierung für die AQAP 2000:2007 notwendig sind.
Nach Stand vom 18.09.2012 erklären wir für Ihr Unternehmen, die TCS GmbH in Heilbronn die Konformität zu nachstehenden Zertifizierungsnormen:
Ihr Unternehmen hat ein konformes Qualitätssicherungssystem, das zu 100% konform mit der DIN ISO 9001 :2000 geht. Dies ist schon aus der Vorzertifizierung nach DIN ISO 9001 :2000 ersichtlich, die aufgrund der höherwertigen AQAP Zertifizierung nach Auslauf im März 2012 nicht verlängert wurde. Dennoch ist die Konformität gegeben.
Über die DIN ISO 9001 :2000 hinaus weist Ihr Unternehmen sogar sämtliche
Voraussetzungen vor, die für eine Zertifizierung nach dem IRIS (International Railway

Europäisch anerkanntes Zertifizierungs- und Trainingsinstitut Nr.: 1 1 78 04856 78 Industry Standard) Standard auf. Dies könnte für Ihr Unternehmen interessant sein, da Sie ebenfalls im Bereich der Bahnindustrie tätig sind.
Ihr Dokumentationssystem wird derzeit zur Vollendung des letzten Schrittes zur
Zertifizierung nach AQAP auf eine IETD (Interaktive Elektronische Technische Seite | 2
Dokumentation) nach allgemeingültigen SIOOOD und S2000M Standards umgestellt. Hier wird die spezielle Spezifikation nach 1388 2b angewandt, die im Gegensatz zum normalen SI 000D Standard als erheblich umfangreicher anzusehen ist.
In jedem Fall erklären wir als LGM GmbH und anerkanntes Institut für Zertifizierung und

Energy efficiency and CO2 net zero are the new standard within a 
sustainable real estate sector. Taking sustainable building materials 
into account, a rent premium can be realized which increases return 
on investment. Additionally, it is expected that regulatory 
requirements will tighten and influence further certification needs.Renewable energy generation for the dedicated real estate 
developments and further consumer in proximity
Greening of cladding, roofs and further areas for benefit of the 
overall population

construction phases as well as eligible for revitalization
Redevelopment and revitalization of densified areas
Affordable housing creates the broadest opportunities for real impact 
investing within the real estate industry. Additionally, architecture
and the choice in building materials are influenced by its effects on 
health and well being. A viable security concepts are of high 
importance in urban residential areas.High value affordable housing and adequate tenant selection

high influence on the tenants and the livability

employees and further stakeholder

green and public spaces

SIZE: 1126178 bytes
CONTENT:


Basis des Green-Safe-House-Systems
Superkondensator Technologie
Die im Green-Safe-House-System  eingesetzten Superkondensatoren 
können anders als Batterien sehr schnell große Energiemengen 
speichern und ebenso schnell wieder abgeben. Bremst beispielsweise 
ein Zug bei der Einfahrt in den Bahnhof ab, speichern Super-
kondensatoren die Leistung und stellen sie wieder bereit, wenn der 
Zug beim Anfahren sehr schnell sehr viel Energie braucht.
Ein Problem der Superkondensatoren war bislang jedoch ihre geringe Energiedichte. Während Lithiumionen-Akku-
mulatoren eine Energiedichte im aktuellen maximalen Feldansatz von 170 Wattstunden pro Kilogramm (Wh/kg) 
erreichen, liefern bisherige Superkondensatoren lediglich ein Zehntel davon. Der neue Superkondensator nutzt ein 
nachhaltiges Graphen-Hybridmaterial als positive Elektrode. Die Forscher kombinierten es mit einer schon 
bewährten, auf Titan und Kohlenstoff basierenden negativen Elektrode. Der Energiespeicher erzielt damit nicht nur 
eine Energiedichte von bis zu 127 Wh/kg, was in etwa der Energiedichte der bei Porsche eingesetzten Lithium Ionen-
Akkus entspricht, sondern leistet mit seiner Leistungsdichte auch deutlich mehr als die meisten anderen 
Superkondensatoren. Das Geheimnis des neuen Superkondensators ist die Kombination verschiedener Materialien –
Chemiker nennen den Superkondensator daher asymmetrisch.


Energiespeichersystem:
10 kW Lade/-Entladeleistung pro Unit
Kapazität: 5/10/15 kWh Units
Mehr als 20.000 bis zu 100.000 Lade/-
Entladezyklen 
Basisvariante: max. 45 kWh möglich 
Options Ausbaupaket Zusatzvariante: 
max. 90 kWh möglich

PARTIZIPATIONSSCHEINE DER T.C.S. SA REGLEMENT

Reglement über die Ausgabe von Partizipationsscheinen der T.C.S. Tactical Combat Systems SA (T.C.S. SA) gemäß Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023
über die Ausgabe von Partizipationsscheinen der T.C.S. Tactical Combat Systems SA Stand 1. März 2024
Allgemeine Bestimmungen
Grundsatz
Die T.C.S. SA kann gemäß Art.656a des Gesetzes Fassung gemäß Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023
Partizipationsscheine (PS) ausgeben.
Sie strebt dabei eine möglichst breite Streuung des PS-Besitzes an. Das Partizipationskapital darf das Grundkapitals übersteigen.

Ausgabe
Über die Ausgabe beschließt der T.C.S. SA Verwaltungsrat. Er bestimmt die Anzahl der PS, deren Nennwert und den Emissionspreis. Das PS- Kapital ist voll zu liberieren.

Ausgestaltung des PS
Die PS lauten auf den Nennwert. Sie werden entweder in einer Globalurkunde auf Dauer verbrieft oder können auch als Wertrechte auf den Inhaber ausgegeben werden. Es besteht kein Anspruch auf ein Wertpapier massige Ausgabe bzw. Auslieferung des PS.
Agio
Der bei der Ausgabe von PS nach Abzug der Ausgabekosten gegenüber dem Nennwert erzielte Mehrerlös (Agio) wird dem Reservefonds (allgemeine gesetzliche Reserve) zugewiesen (§ 24 Abs. 1 T.C.S. SAG).

Börsenkotierung
Die PS werden, im OTC Markt kotiert. bis zu einem IPO an einer Schweizer oder anderen Börse
Rechtsstellung der Partizipanten
Dividende
Die PS geben im Rahmen der gesetzlichen Bestimmungen Anrecht auf eine Dividende, die im gleichen Verhältnis zum Nennwert der PS steht wie die Summe der Verzinsung des Grundkapitals und der Gewinnablieferung zum Grundkapital.
Bezugsrecht
Bei Erhöhung des Grundkapitals haben die Partizipanten* keinen Anspruch auf Beteiligung am Grundkapital. Dies gilt auch für den Fall, dass das Grundkapital allein oder stärker erhöht wird als das Partizipationskapital. Solange keine Partizipationsscheine begeben sind, erfolgt die Erhöhung des Grundkapitals oder die Umwandlung von Grund- in Partizipationskapital zum Nominalwert. Sind Partizipationsscheine begeben, ist der Marktwert der Partizipationsscheine zu berücksichtigen. Bei der Ausgabe neuer Partizipationsscheine hat jeder Partizipant im Rahmen seines Bezugsrechts Anspruch auf den Teil der neu ausgegebenen Partizipationsscheine, der seiner bisherigen Beteiligung am Partizipationskapital entspricht. Wird Grundkapital in Partizipationskapital umgewandelt, steht den Partizipanten kein Bezugsrecht zu. Das Bezugsrecht kann vom T.C.S. SA Verwaltungsrat aus wichtigen Gründen ganz oder teilweise ausgeschlossen werden. Durch die Aufhebung des Bezugsrechts aus wichtigen Gründen darf niemand in unsachlicher Weise begünstigt werden. * dieser Begriff steht stellvertretend für Inhaberinnen und Inhaber von Partizipationsscheinen
Kapitalsanierung und Liquidationsanteil
Bei einer allfälligen Kapitalsanierung werden Grundkapital und PS-Kapital gleichbehandelt. Die Partizipanten haben Anrecht auf einen verhältnismäßigen Anteil am Ergebnis einer allfälligen Liquidation. Die Änderung der Rechtsform der T.C.S. Tactical Combat Systems SA gilt nicht als Liquidation.
Recht auf Information
Die Partizipanten haben auf Verlangen Anspruch auf Aushändigung des vorliegenden Reglements. Informationen zum Geschäftsbericht der T.C.S. SA. werden ausschließlich dem Verwaltungsrats Vorsitzenden der Steubing AG Goethestraße 29, 60313 Frankfurt am Main gewährt.
Der T.C.S. SA Verwaltungsrat kann die Partizipanten zu Versammlungen einladen und sie über den Geschäftsverlauf der T.C.S. SA unterrichten. Der Versammlung der Partizipanten kommt lediglich eine Informations- und keine Organfunktion zu. Sie kann insbesondere keine verbindlichen Beschlüsse fassen. Die Beantwortung von Fragen, die der T.C.S. SA mindestens zwei Wochen vor der Versammlung der Partizipanten schriftlich zugegangen sein müssen, erfolgt nur an dieser Versammlung. Gemäß Reglement über die Ausgabe von Partizipationsscheinen der T.C.S. Tactical Combat Systems SA Stand 1. März 2024.
Auskünfte können insbesondere verweigert werden, wenn durch sie das Geschäfts- oder T.C.S. SA Kundengeheimnis oder andere schutzwürdige Interessen der T.C.S. SA gefährdet werden.
Gleichbehandlung
Die Schaffung von Vorzugs-PS ist nicht zulässig.
Fehlen des Mitwirkungsrechtes
Die Partizipanten haben keine Mitwirkungsrechte. Die Beschlüsse der T.C.S. SA Organe im Rahmen des T.C.S. SA Satzung, insbesondere über die Genehmigung der Jahresrechnung und des Geschäftsberichtes sowie über die Verwendung des Reingewinnes, sind für die Partizipanten rechtsverbindlich.
Mitteilungen
Einladungen und Mitteilungen an die Partizipanten erfolgen durch einmalige Veröffentlichung im Schweizerischen Handelsamtsblatt (SHAB) und im Amtsblatt des Kantons Tessin sowie in einer im Kanton Tessin erscheinenden Tageszeitung.
Schlussbestimmungen
Grundsatz und Ergänzung des Reglements
Der T.C.S. SA Verwaltungsrat kann das vorliegende Reglement jederzeit abändern unter Vorbehalt der den Partizipanten eingeräumten Rechte auf Gleichbehandlung, Dividende und Information sowie unter Vorbehalt der Pflichten im Zusammenhang mit einer allfälligen Kapitalsanierung oder Liquidation.
Subsidiäres Recht
Für die Ausgabe, die Rechtsstellung der Partizipanten, das PS-Kapital und die PS gelten, soweit in diesem Reglement nichts anderes bestimmt wird, die Vorschriften des Schweizerischen Obligationenrechts sinngemäß.
Inkrafttreten Grundlage für dieses Reglement
Das Reglement ist vom Verwaltungsrat der T.C.S. Tactical Combat Systems SA genehmigt worden. Es tritt per 1. März 2024 in Kraft.


Lugano den 29.2.2024


T.C.S. SA
Verwaltungsrat Susanna Hartenbach
A:  Genussscheine Voraussetzung

430 Fassung gemäss Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).
Art. 657431

1 Die Statuten können die Schaffung von Genussscheinen zugunsten von Personen vorsehen, die mit der Gesellschaft durch frühere Kapitalbeteiligung oder als Aktionär, Gläubiger, Arbeitnehmer oder in ähnlicher Weise verbunden sind. Sie haben die Zahl der ausgegebenen Genussscheine und den Inhalt der damit verbundenen Rechte anzugeben.

2 Durch die Genussscheine können den Berechtigten nur Ansprüche auf einen Anteil am Bilanzgewinn oder am Liquidationsergebnis oder auf den Bezug neuer Aktien verliehen werden.

3 Der Genussschein darf keinen Nennwert haben; er darf weder Partizipationsschein genannt noch gegen eine Einlage ausgegeben werden, die unter den Aktiven der Bilanz ausgewiesen wird.

4 Die Berechtigten bilden von Gesetzes wegen eine Gemeinschaft, für welche die Bestimmungen über die Gläubigergemeinschaft bei Anleihensobligationen sinngemäss gelten. Den Verzicht auf einzelne oder alle Rechte aus den Genussscheinen können jedoch nur die Inhaber der Mehrheit aller im Umlauf befindlichen Genussscheintitel verbindlich beschliessen.
5 Zugunsten der Gründer der Gesellschaft dürfen Genussscheine nur aufgrund der ursprünglichen Statuten geschaffen werden.

B: J. Partizipationsscheine
I. Begriff; anwendbare Vorschriften415
415 Fassung gemäss Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).
Art. 656a416

1 Die Statuten können ein Partizipationskapital vorsehen, das in Teilsummen (Partizipationsscheine) zerlegt ist. Diese Partizipationsscheine müssen auf dieselbe Währung wie das Aktienkapital lauten. Sie werden gegen Einlage ausgegeben, haben einen Nennwert und gewähren kein Stimmrecht.417

2 Die Bestimmungen über das Aktienkapital, die Aktie und den Aktionär gelten, soweit das Gesetz nichts anderes vorsieht, auch für das Partizipationskapital, den Partizipationsschein und den Partizipanten.
3 Die Partizipationsscheine sind als solche zu bezeichnen.
4 Partizipationskapital kann geschaffen werden:
1.
bei der Gründung;
2.
durch ordentliche Kapitalerhöhung;
3.
durch Kapitalerhöhung aus bedingtem Kapital;
4.
innerhalb eines Kapitalbands.418
5 Die Umwandlung von Aktien in Partizipationsscheine bedarf der Zustimmung sämtlicher betroffener Aktionäre.419
416 Eingefügt durch Ziff. I des BG vom 4. Okt. 1991, in Kraft seit 1. Juli 1992 (AS 1992 733; BBl 1983 II 745).
417 Fassung gemäss Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).
418 Eingefügt durch Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).
419 Eingefügt durch Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).
II. Partizipations- und Aktienkapital
Art. 656b420

1 Der Anteil des Partizipationskapitals, der sich aus Partizipationsscheinen zusammensetzt, die an einer Börse kotiert sind, darf das Zehnfache des im Handelsregister eingetragenen Aktienkapitals nicht übersteigen. Der übrige Teil des Partizipationskapitals darf das Doppelte des im Handelsregister eingetragenen Aktienkapitals nicht übersteigen.
2 Die Bestimmungen über das Mindestkapital finden keine Anwendung.
3 Das Partizipationskapital ist dem Aktienkapital zuzurechnen bei:
1.
der Bildung der gesetzlichen Gewinnreserve;
2.
der Verwendung der gesetzlichen Kapital- und Gewinnreserven;
3.
der Beurteilung, ob eine Unterbilanz oder ein Kapitalverlust vorliegt;
4.
der Beschränkung des Umfangs einer Erhöhung des Kapitals aus bedingtem Kapital;
5.
der Festlegung der unteren und der oberen Grenze eines Kapitalbands.
4 Die Schwellenwerte sind für Aktionäre und Partizipanten gesondert zu berechnen bei:
1.
der Einleitung einer Sonderuntersuchung im Fall der Ablehnung eines entsprechenden Antrags durch die Generalversammlung;
2.
der Auflösung der Gesellschaft durch Urteil des Gerichts;
3.
der Meldung der wirtschaftlich berechtigten Person gemäss Artikel 697j.
5 Sie werden berechnet:
1.
für den Erwerb eigener Aktien auf der Grundlage der ausgegebenen Aktien;
2.
für den Erwerb eigener Partizipationsscheine auf der Grundlage der ausgegebenen Partizipationsscheine.
6 Sie sind ausschliesslich auf der Grundlage des Aktienkapitals zu berechnen:
1.
für das Recht auf Einberufung der Generalversammlung;
2.
für das Traktandierungs- und Antragsrecht.
420 Eingefügt durch Ziff. I des BG vom 4. Okt. 1991 (AS 1992 733; BBl 1983 II 745). Fassung gemäss Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020
(Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).

III. Rechtsstellung des Partizipanten
1. Im Allgemeinen
Art. 656c421

1 Der Partizipant hat kein Stimmrecht und, sofern die Statuten nichts anderes bestimmen, keines der damit zusammenhängenden Rechte.

2 Als mit dem Stimmrecht zusammenhängende Rechte gelten das Recht auf Einberufung einer Generalversammlung, das Teilnahmerecht, das Recht auf Auskunft, das Recht auf Einsicht und das Traktandierungs- und Antragsrecht.422

3 Unter den gleichen Voraussetzungen wie der Aktionär hat der Partizipant ein Recht auf Einleitung einer Sonderuntersuchung. Sehen die Statuten keine weitergehenden Rechte vor, so kann der Partizipant Begehren um Auskunft, Einsicht und Einleitung einer Sonderuntersuchung schriftlich zuhanden der Generalversammlung stellen.423
421 Eingefügt durch Ziff. I des BG vom 4. Okt. 1991, in Kraft seit 1. Juli 1992 (AS 1992 733; BBl 1983 II 745).
422 Fassung gemäss Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).
423 Fassung gemäss Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).

2. Bekanntgabe der Einberufung und Information über Generalversammlungsbeschlüsse424
424 Fassung gemäss Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).
Art. 656d425

1 Den Partizipanten muss die Einberufung der Generalversammlung zusammen mit den Verhandlungsgegenständen und den Anträgen bekannt gegeben werden.
2 Jeder Partizipant kann verlangen, dass ihm das Protokoll innerhalb von 30 Tagen nach der Generalversammlung zugänglich gemacht wird.426
425 Eingefügt durch Ziff. I des BG vom 4. Okt. 1991, in Kraft seit 1. Juli 1992 (AS 1992 733; BBl 1983 II 745).
426 Fassung gemäss Ziff. I des BG vom 19. Juni 2020 (Aktienrecht), in Kraft seit 1. Jan. 2023 (AS 2020 4005; 2022 109; BBl 2017 399).
3. Vertretung im Verwaltungsrat
Art. 656e427

Die Statuten können den Partizipanten einen Anspruch auf einen Vertreter im Verwaltungsrat einräumen.
4. Vermögensrechte
a. Im Allgemeinen
Art. 656f 428

1 Die Statuten dürfen die Partizipanten bei der Verteilung des Bilanzgewinnes und des Liquidationsergebnisses sowie beim Bezug neuer Aktien nicht schlechter stellen als die Aktionäre.

2 Bestehen mehrere Kategorien von Aktien, so müssen die Partizipationsscheine zumindest der Kategorie gleichgestellt sein, die am wenigsten bevorzugt ist.

3 Statutenänderungen und andere Generalversammlungsbeschlüsse, welche die Stellung der Partizipanten verschlechtern, sind nur zulässig, wenn sie auch die Stellung der Aktionäre, denen die Partizipanten gleichstehen, entsprechend beeinträchtigen.
4 Sofern die Statuten nichts anderes bestimmen, dürfen die Vorrechte und die statutarischen Mitwirkungsrechte von Partizipanten nur mit Zustimmung einer besonderen Versammlung der betroffenen Partizipanten und der Generalversammlung der Aktionäre beschränkt oder aufgehoben werden.
428 Eingefügt durch Ziff. I des BG vom 4. Okt. 1991, in Kraft seit 1. Juli 1992 (AS 1992 733; BBl 1983 II 745).
b. Bezugsrechte
Art. 656g429

1 Wird ein Partizipationskapital geschaffen, so haben die Aktionäre ein Bezugsrecht wie bei der Ausgabe neuer Aktien.

2 Die Statuten können vorsehen, dass Aktionäre nur Aktien und Partizipanten nur Partizipationsscheine beziehen können, wenn das Aktien- und das Partizipationskapital gleichzeitig und im gleichen Verhältnis erhöht werden.

3 Wird das Partizipationskapital oder das Aktienkapital allein oder verhältnismässig stärker als das andere erhöht, so sind die Bezugsrechte so zuzuteilen, dass Aktionäre und Partizipanten am gesamten Kapital gleich wie bis anhin beteiligt bleiben können.
429 Eingefügt durch Ziff. I des BG vom 4. Okt. 1991, in Kraft seit 1. Juli 1992 (AS 1992 733; BBl 1983 II 745).

Wastewaterplants
Lessinput-getthemostoutofit!
Water is one of our most valuable natural products. Toeconomize the use of water
Using valuable drinking water for cleaning train is economically not acceptable. 
Therefore it makes sense to develop new innovative concepts in order to reuse the 
used water multiple times.
The goals of water protection politics permanently define increasing requirements 
on advanced effluent treatment.
Increasing costs for drinking water and wastewater as well as ecological considera-
tions demand us to complete the economical aspect very intensively.
Superior TCS-system-technology guarantees environmentally friendly cleansing technology,
because water is one of our most valuable natural products.
Therefore,TCSsets the priority:
„Beeconomicallywithwater.“

CONTENT:
Prozesstechnologie für Ihre Prozesse






























	









	



SAH/TCS - seit 30 Jahren unter anderem im industriellen Engineering petrochemischen Großanlagenbau tätig - ist nicht nur Initiator und treibende Kraft der Entwicklung des Autarkie EMS-Systems sondern hat das System überdies für das eigene Unternehmen notwendigerweise entwickelt und in Betrieb genommen, da nach eingehender weltweiter Marktanalyse festgestellt werden musste, dass es kein funktionsfähiges Systeme am Markt gibt, welches dem unternehmerischen und wirtschaftlichen Anspruch „total cost of ownership“ und „return of investment“ der SAH gerecht wird. Nach dem niederschmetternden Ergebnis der ausgiebigen technischen und wirtschaftlichen Marktanalyse sah sich die S.A.H. dazu genötigt, ein vollfunktionsfähiges wirtschaftlich tragfähiges Autarkie-EMS -System eigenständig unter Einsatz sämtlicher, im Laufe der Firmenhistorie aus allen Fachgebieten erworbenen, Engineering Know Hows und aller verbundenen Unternehmen aus dem
industriellen petrochemischen Bereich
militärischen Bereich
Kernkraftwerksbereich + Energieverteilung Planung + Bau
verfahrenstechnischen Bereich


Die Systemlogik



Das System hat einen effizienten Sommerbetrieb, bei dem PV-Strom und Wärmepumpe, sowie die Speicher optimal eingesetzt werden können. Eine Zuführung von Energie aus dem Netz ist möglich und wird ggf. für Spitzenbelastungen benötigt. In der kalten Jahreszeit muss teilweise auf das Ersatzstromaggregat zurückgegriffen werden. Da dieser Erzeuger mit einer Leistung von nur 7,5 KW arbeitet, ergibt sich nur eine sehr geringe Verbrauchsbelastung. (vgl. Anhang).
Die Integration verschiedener Komponenten (Gleichrichter, Solaranlage, Wärmepumpe und Speichermedium) und deren Einbau in das Gesamtsystem ermöglichen eine Systemautarkie und einen niedrigen Verbrauch und den sehr geringen ökologischen Footprint in der Gesamtperiode.


Basis des Green-Safe-House-Systems


Superkondensator Technologie
Die im Green-Safe-House-System eingesetzten Superkondensatoren können anders als Batterien sehr schnell große Energiemengen speichern und ebenso schnell wieder abgeben. Bremst beispielsweise ein Zug bei der Einfahrt in den Bahnhof ab, speichern Super- kondensatoren die Leistung und stellen sie wieder bereit, wenn der Zug beim Anfahren sehr schnell sehr viel Energie braucht.



Ein Problem der Superkondensatoren war bislang jedoch ihre geringe Energiedichte. Während Lithiumionen-Akku- mulatoren eine Energiedichte im aktuellen maximalen Feldansatz von 170 Wattstunden pro Kilogramm (Wh/kg)
erreichen, liefern bisherige Superkondensatoren lediglich ein Zehntel davon. Der neue Superkondensator nutzt ein nachhaltiges Graphen-Hybridmaterial als positive Elektrode. Die Forscher kombinierten es mit einer schon bewährten, auf Titan und Kohlenstoff basierenden negativen Elektrode. Der Energiespeicher erzielt damit nicht nur eine Energiedichte von bis zu 127 Wh/kg, was in etwa der Energiedichte der bei Porsche eingesetzten Lithium Ionen- Akkus entspricht, sondern leistet mit seiner Leistungsdichte auch deutlich mehr als die meisten anderen Superkondensatoren. Das Geheimnis des neuen Superkondensators ist die Kombination verschiedener Materialien – Chemiker nennen den Superkondensator daher asymmetrisch.



Autarkie bedeutetet, dass über einen längeren Zeitraum Strom und Wärme eigenständig erzeugt werden und Versorgungsstörungen im Stromnetz ohne Einschränkungen an Komfort überbrückt werden können. Eine permanente unterbrechungsfreie Versorgung eines Gebäudekomplexes soll dabei zusätzlich das Kriterium der Wirtschaftlichkeit erfüllen. Das angesprochene System soll also nicht wie traditionelle System nur Preisschwankungen in den Energiemärkten ausgleichen, sondern darüber hinaus Versorgungssicherheit unabhängig von herrschenden Energiemarktbedingungen herstellen.
Der zweite Aspekt betrifft das Motiv und die Logik des zugrunde liegenden Engineerings.
Das zentrale Motiv für die Entwicklung eines solchen Autarkiesystems war die Erkenntnis, dass Systeme zur Versorgung einzelner Gebäude entweder nicht am Markt verfügbar sind und sie allenfalls durch extrem teuere Einzelobjektplanungen realisierbar sind. Aber nicht nur der Preis wäre ein erhebliches Hindernis für die Nutzung einer solchen Anlage, sondern auch die notwendigen Genehmigungen, die erforderlichen Maintenance, die Ersatzteilbeschaffung sowie das Handling der Gesamtkomplexität durch das lokale Fachhandwerk (Sanitär/Elektrofachbetriebe) verhindern eine wirtschaftliche Umsetzung eines solchen Projektes.
Bei der Suche nach einer praktikablen, autarken Lösung war schnell klar, dass die bestehenden Systeme primär Einzeloptimierungen vorsehen, etwa bei einzelnen Erzeugungsarten (Solar- oder kleine Windkraftanlagen) oder zum Ziel haben, eine Technik (z.B. Wärmetauscher auf Luft oder Wasserbasis ) in seinen Wirkungsgraden zu verbessern. Ein singuläres Erzeugungs- oder auch Speichersystem war jedoch bisher unter den bestehenden Bedingungen nicht realisierbar. Ein praktikables System mußte daher - so die Erkenntnis - aus verschiedenartigen Einzelkomponenten (Speicher- und Erzeugerkomponenten) bestehen. Die Systemkomponenten sollten technisch einwandfrei und wirtschaftlich optimal arbeiten. Die Idee einer Plattform als Steuerungssystem für die diversen Komponenten der Erzeugung und Speicherung von Energie war geboren. An diese Plattform sollten beliebige Arten von Energieerzeugern und - speichern angeschlossen werden können. (Die Integration von kleinen Windkraftanlagen etwa ist ohne Problem möglich).Mit einem solchen System, das technisch mit den Anforderungen der EVUs konform ist, konnten jetzt die weiteren Überlegungen zu den Komponenten und deren Zusammenwirken beginnen. Die bei der Entwicklung beteiligten Experten aus den Bereichen, Großanlagenbau, Automatisierungstechnik haben dann auf im industriellen Großanlagenbau seit Jahrzehnten übliche Prinzipien zurückgegriffen und daraus ein System entwickelt, das folgende Erfordernisse berücksichtigt:

Einhaltung bestimmter technischer Funktionalitäten (Versorgung eines Gebäudes mit Strom und Wärme)
Einbau von Mehrfachredundanzen für einen störungsfreien Betrieb
Minimierung der erforderlichen Maintenance und - sofern überhaupt erforderlich - deren Sicherstellung durch das örtliche Handwerk
Kosteneffizienz





Setzt man die Batterie im Zusammenhang mit PV-Technologie ein, so werden die Speicher häufig be- und entladen. Die Kondensatortechnologie schafft hier neue Möglichkeiten, die insbesondere bei einer „total cost of ownership“-Betrachtung längerfristig von großem Vorteil sind. Die Technologie hat gegenüber Lithium-Batterien im autarken EMS System einen erheblichen Vorteil und lässt sich damit in die Logik von Erzeugung, Speicherung und Abgabe deutlich besser einsetzen. Die neuen Technologien machen erst ein effizientes Zusammenspiel der verschiedenen Erzeuger- und Speicherkomponenten wirtschaftlich möglich.

Die Zentrale Plattform Technologie

TCS GREEN SAFE House combines a multi-function port future power electric panel in the house, replacing the conventional electric panel in the house today by using every Green Energy supply that is available to 100% for self use without necessary Power Grid connection and zero grid power feed-in
All In One Solution System combines following features

State of the Art Power Electric Box to the Regulations §14a EnWG +VDE-AR-N4105
+4100 (Smart Meter Ready)
Automated Integreatetd Power Grid Disconnection Netlevel 7 due to Grid regulations
Complet Online USV Functionality for the Household Powersupply
Over and Undervoltage Saftey protection from Grid included
Lightnig Protection included
100% EMP Saftey after NATO military standard
100 percent Selfsupply and Black Start Capable (Start up without Grid connection or extern powersupply)
100 percent continuous power Supply Operation
The world's only technology that can use all energy generators simultaneously for its own needs
Worldwide Unique Technologie that uses all Energy Supply Forms in parallel simultaneously ( adding up all diffrent energysource at ones)for Energy Self supply
Only System Worldwide that is 100% phase unbalanced load capable
Only System Worlwide that can work independent of the 50/60 Hertz (internal and external)
Complete PV/Wind/Water Turbines Electric + Saftey regulations Installation already included
Excess E-Charge Function + Wallbox connection already included
Adjustable throttled 3phase-Synchronous undercoverage power grid supply

Zählerplatztechnik in steckbarer EHZ2 Zähleranschlusstechnik inkl.Smart Meter Messstellenbetreiber Konform Werkseitig integriert

(IEC 60947-6-1 und IEC 60947-3)
